data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both compile and run without issues. The syntax is straightforward:

```csharp
Span<nint> span = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system, `nint.Size` is 8 bytes, so each element occupies a pointer-sized slot on the stack. This has been supported since C# 9 / .NET 5 when `nint`/`nuint` became first-class keywords backed by `System.IntPtr`/`System.UIntPtr` as unmanaged types.
